            <p>Boston Ab 21.5644<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> S. Morais<lb/>
                My very dear Sir<lb/></p> 
            <p>Many kind thanks for<lb/> your very kind article on my<lb/>notice of my poor dear old<lb/> friend Mr. Collamne his<lb/> family are much gratified<lb/> with the notice. On the<lb/> return of Lieut. Greely&#91;&#63;&#93; I<lb/> noticed the name of<lb/> Edward Israel&#44; &#38; wrote to<lb/> the president of War<lb/>department&#44; to know all<lb/> about him. I recd. very kind<lb/> replies from all. I had<lb/> intended if he had no<lb/> family to take personal<lb/> charge of his body &#38; have it entered <hi rend="underline">at New</hi>port R.I.<lb/> Subsequently I heard from<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p><hi rend="underline">his mother</hi>&#44; &#38;  implored that<lb/> his funeral should be<lb/> most strictly orthodox<lb/> which she <sic>promissed</sic> me &#38; <lb/> I sent her some sand<lb/> from the Sacred soil of<lb/> Palestine to be buried<lb/> with him. The enclos&#91;e&#93;d<lb/> letter I just rec<hi rend="sup">d</hi>. from Lieut.<lb/> Greely which is so broad<lb/> &#38; liberal to our <sic>pleople</sic><lb/> I thought you might fix it<lb/> so as to appear in the Record&#91;.&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours faithfully<lb/> in which Mrs Marcus<lb/> &#38; family join to all dear<lb/> to you &#38; remain as ever<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours Most faithfully<lb/>
                Alfred A. Marcus<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
